{
  "doc_id": "23042",
  "text": "additional site for docking to the bromodomain of Brd4, which facilitates E2-dependent transcriptional activation [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . While bromodomains have affinity for most acetylated lysines, they do exhibit binding preference [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . The bromodomain interaction preference on histone H3 and H4 peptides is for diacetylated lysines [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . This would indicate that acetylation of a combination of K111, K112, and possibly K107 would result in a higher-affinity interaction. A cocrystal of the N-terminal region of E2 with a short C-terminal peptide of Brd4 revealed the site of their interaction to span the three alpha helices and not the K111-containing peptide, which is at the N terminus of the beta sheet region [CITATION_9] . However, HPV-11 E2 has been demonstrated to interact with a region containing the second bromodomain of Brd4 in addition to the CTD [CITATION_10] . This supports the possibility that a second region of E2 may also participate in this interaction. Although the structures of several functional domains on Brd4, including both bromodomains and the C-terminal domain that interacts with E2, have been solved, the full-length protein structure has not been reported.",
